{{Quote|<nowiki></nowiki>''Answer:'' He is alive and well and trying to kill ''Han Solo'' on an obscure planet called ''Orleon''.|''Star Wars 28''{{'s}} opening text|<ref name="Star Wars (1977) 28">[[Star Wars (1977) 28|''Star Wars'' (1977) 28]]</ref>}}
'''''Star Wars'' 28''' is the twenty-eighth issue of the [[Star Wars Legends|Legends]] [[Star Wars comic books|comic book]] series [[Star Wars (1977)|''Star Wars'']]. It was written by [[Archie Goodwin]], illustrated by [[Carmine Infantino]], and first published on [[July 24]], [[1979]] by [[Marvel Comics]]. The issue features the story "'''What Ever Happened to Jabba the Hut?'''," in which [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] and [[Chewbacca/Legends|Chewbacca]] evade [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure/Legends|Jabba's]] enforcers and dangerous [[Stone mite/Legends|stone mites]].

In ''Star Wars'' 28, Jabba is depicted as a [[Nimbanel/Legends|Nimbanel]]. Later works would [[Retroactive continuity|retcon]] this depiction as the character of [[Mosep Binneed/Legends|Mosep Binneed]], one of Jabba's underlings who operated with his name.

==Publisher's summary==
''Jabba the Hut is looking to get his payment from Han and Chewie, through deadly force if necessary.''

==Plot summary==
A rough re-entry of the [[Millennium Falcon/Legends|''Millennium Falcon'']] from [[Hyperspace/Legends|hyperspace]] prompts Han Solo and Chewbacca to land on the [[Mid Rim/Legends|Mid Rim]] world [[Orleon]], a [[Smuggler/Legends|smuggler's]] hideout constantly besieged by rain. As Han and Chewbacca make repairs, the [[Wookiee/Legends|Wookiee]] notes that the cavern they had sheltered the ''Falcon'' in is leaking.

Han and Chewbacca's attention is diverted by the arrival of Jabba the Hut. Jabba's forces assault the cavern to drive Han and Chewbacca into the open, but the two smugglers are faced with another problem: the entire cavern ceiling is infested with [[Stone mite/Legends|stone mites]], living weapons from the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]] that can eat through anything.

The stone mites pour onto the ''Falcon'', and Han and Chewbacca barely make it on board. At Han's suggestion, Chewbacca uses the ''Falcon''{{'s}} [[Laser cannon/Legends|laser cannons]] to blast away the cavern roof. The ''Falcon'' escapes through the blasted surface and leaves Orleon, confronting Jabba the Hut's [[Starship/Legends|ship]], the ''[[Voidraker]]'', in [[Orbit/Legends|orbit]].

Through transmissions from the ''Voidraker'', Han and Chewbacca discover that the stone mites have infested Jabba's ship. As the only survivor, Jabba pleads with Han for sanctuary on the ''Falcon''. Jabba jets over in his flight suit, but Han's "payment" for allowing him sanctuary (''on'' the ship, not in it) is that his and Chewbacca's debts are canceled.

==Continuity==
The official [[StarWars.com]] [[Databank (original)|Databank]] entry for Jabba the Hutt recounts the events of ''Star Wars'' 28 and states that "While this particular version of these events didn't happen, it is still possible that the Orleon incident did occur."<ref name="DB">{{DB|character|jabbathehutt|Jabba the Hutt}}</ref>

The [[2014]] article "[[Red Five (department)|Red Five]]," published in [[Star Wars Insider 149|''Star Wars Insider'' 149]], established that the "Jabba" in [[Star Wars (1977)|''Star Wars'']] was in fact Jabba's [[Nimbanel/Legends|Nimbanel]] accountant, [[Mosep Binneed/Legends|Mosep Binneed]], who sometimes used Jabba's name in interactions.<ref name="Red Five">{{InsiderCite|149|Red Five|Red Five: John Jackson Miller}}</ref>

